class Solution {
    public int bitwiseComplement(int n) {
        StringBuilder sd=new StringBuilder(Integer.toBinaryString(n));
        for(int i=0;i<sd.length();i++){
            char ch=sd.charAt(i);
            if(ch=='0'){
                sd.setCharAt(i,'1');
            }
            else{
                sd.setCharAt(i,'0');
            }
        }
    return Integer.parseInt(sd.toString(),2);    }
}

Note: 
The number n is first converted into its binary form using Integer.toBinaryString() and stored in a StringBuilder
so the bits can be modified easily. Then the program loops through each bit and flips it: if the bit is '0' it becomes '1', 
and if it is '1' it becomes '0'. Finally, the modified binary string is converted back to a decimal integer using Integer.parseInt(..., 2) and returned
as the complement.
